@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Imports Go To Buffer"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Imports Go To Buffer                                                  @{fg text}@{uu}

This gadget allows you to separate any file(s) you import,  from the
ones that are currently displayed by QLib.  When checked, all  files
imported will go to a separate buffer that can be viewed by changing
the main list to "Buffer".

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Get Revision From..."
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Get Revision From...                                                  @{fg text}@{uu}

By  reading  a  files  segment data we can get information such as the
IdString  and  version but NOT the revision.  The revision is obtained
by  opening  the  library  structure for the file or by looking at the
IdString.  QLib offers three choices in this area.

@{fg shine}    Get Revision From IdString. @{fg text}
   QLib will try to get the revision by scanning the IdString.  Always
   keep  in  mind  that the IdString is just text and may not actually
   have  a  revision  or  the  revision  may  actually be incorrect as
   compared to opening the library data for the file.

@{fg shine}    Get Revision From Library Structure. @{fg text}
   Very simply, this method will open the library  structure  for  the
   revision. This is slower and prone to side effects.

@{fg shine}    Get Revision From Both. @{fg text}
   This  is probably the best option. The IdString will be scanned for
   revision.  If, and only if,  the  revision  is  not  found will the
   library structure be opened.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Comment Insert Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Comment Insert Gadget                                                 @{fg text}@{uu}

The  comment  insert  gadget  is located in two places.  From the main
window below the listview identified by "<".  And on the report window
to  the right of the @{"comment" link "Comment Gadget"} string gadget.  The comment insert gadget
inserts, into the comment field, one of two possible types of comments,
based on your @{"preferences" link "PrefsWindow"}.

@{fg shine}Comment Inserts Use IdString @{fg text}
The  IdString  will  be  copied into the comment field overwriting the
existing comment.

@{fg shine}Comment Inserts Use Version.Revision@{fg text}
The  version  and  revision  are  inserted  in  one  of three possible
manners.   It  may be inserted as a prefix before the comment becoming
part  of  the original; as a suffix after the comment, still retaining
the  original  or  an  overwrite  which  will  not retain the original
comment, leaving only the Version.Revision as the comment.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Disable String"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Disable String                                                        @{fg text}@{uu}

The  "Disable  String"  allows you to quickly disable a file by either
prefixing  or  suffixing  the  file with the "disable string" that you
specify.   The  "disable string" should be 2-16 characters.  The radio
buttons allow you to select between prefix/suffix

@endnode


@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ReportWindow
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Report Window                                                         @{fg text}@{uu}

Double  Clicking  an entry from the list on the main window will cause
the  report window to open for the item you selected.  If the item has
not  all  ready  been  scanned  then QLib will scan it and present the
information.   With  the  report window still open you can continue to
select  items  from  the  main  window.  The report window will update
itself.   To scan an item again simply double click on another item or
select one of the scan gadgets from the main window.

    @{fg shine}The Report@{fg text}

    Dos Name...... @{"Dos Name" link "Dos Name Gadget"} of file.
    Comment....... @{"Comment" link "Comment Gadget"} string for file.
    Path.......... The DOS path where the file is located.
    Seg Name...... Internal segment name.
    IdString...... Internal Id string.
    Version....... Version.
    Revision...... Revision.
    Priority...... Priority.
    Size.......... Dos size of file in bytes.


@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Dos Name Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Dos Name Gadget                                                       @{fg text}@{uu}

The  Dos  Name gadget allows you to rename the file you have selected.
QLib will ask you to confirm the renaming before proceeding.  Renaming
a file allows you to temporarily disable it, but caution should always
be used when renaming.

@{bg fill}                                                                      @{bg back}
@{fg shine}                           W A R N I N G@{fg text}
If your not too sure about renaming system files or why they are there
then  DO  NOT  rename  anything.   The  ability  to  rename is for the
informed  user.   Renaming  a  file  displayed  by  QLib could disable
software on your system or worse cripple portions of your system.
@{bg fill}                                                                      @{bg back}

@endnode


@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Comment Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Comment Gadget                                                        @{fg text}@{uu}

On  the  report  window  there  is a string gadget for the dos comment
allowing  you  to  edit  the comment.  When you hit return, after your
changes  QLib  will  automatically update the comment on disk.  To the
right  of the comment string gadget there is a small gadget identified
by  a  "<"  symbol.  This is the @{"comment insert" link "Comment Insert Gadget"} gadget.  Clicking on
this  will  copy  either  the  IdString  or  version.revision into the
comment  field  depending and on what you have set your @{"preferences" link "PrefsWindow"}
to  for  "Comment Inserts". The @{"comment insert" link "Comment Insert Gadget"} gadget is also on the
main window for convenience.  If the length of the comment exceeds the
allowed  length for a dos file comment of 80 characters then QLib will
detect this and ask you if you want to truncate the comment.

@endnode


@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "List View Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Main ListView Gadget                                                  @{fg text}@{uu}

The  main  windows  listview  gadget  displays  the  files  that  QLib
recognizes.  There are three columns in the list.  The leftmost column
displays  the file name and extension.  The middle column displays the
version and revision.  The revision will only be displayed if you have
scanned the file and QLib was able to get the revision.  The rightmost
column  displays the comment for that file.  Clicking once on an entry
in  the  list  will  display  the  comment  string below the listview.
Double  clicking  on an entry will bring up the report window for that
file.   When  the report window opens, a scan of the file will be done
if one hasn't been done already.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Scan Gadgets"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Scan & Scan All Gadgets                                               @{fg text}@{uu}

Scan  will scan a file that you have selected from the list.  The scan
will  try  to  get  the version and revision numbers as well as the ID
String for the file.  Scan All will scan all the files that are in the
currently displayed list.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "File Type Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
File Type Cycle Gadget                                                @{fg text}@{uu}

In  the middle of the main window below the listview gadget there is a
cycle  gadget containing several entries.  These entries represent the
files that QLib recognizes.  Currently these are...
@{fg shine}
 Libraries
 Classes
 Datatypes
 Device
 Images
 Gadgets
@{fg text}
When QLib starts up it will scan your system for these files. You can
select what file types are displayed by using the cycle gadget.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Import Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Import Gadget                                                                @{fg text}@{uu}

By default, QLib looks at the standard system locations for files as follows.

  @{fg shine}Datatypes   @{fg text}in  SYS:Classes/DataTypes
  @{fg shine}Gadgets     @{fg text}in  SYS:Classes/Gadgets
  @{fg shine}Images      @{fg text}in  SYS:Classes/Images
  @{fg shine}Classes     @{fg text}in  SYS:Classes/
  @{fg shine}Devices     @{fg text}in  DEVS:
  @{fg shine}Libraries   @{fg text}in  LIBS:

You  may  have  files in a different location or you might have a file
that you want to check before you put it on your system.  In this case
you can use the @{fg shine}IMPORT@{fg text} gadget.  A multi-select file requester will pop
up  from which you may select your file(s).  When a selection is made,
QLib will insert your selection in two possible ways.  If you have the
@{fg shine}"Imports Go To Buffer"@{fg text} gadget  checked in  your @{"preferences" link "PrefsWindow"} then  any
file you select will go into a separate buffer that can be viewed from
the  main  list  by  switching the cycle gadget to  buffer.  Otherwise
QLib  will  separate  the  files and put them into their corresponding
file type display with any other files that might exist.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Refresh Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Refresh Gadget                                                        @{fg text}@{uu}

The  refresh  gadget will rescan your system for the file type that is
currently being displayed in the listview gadget.

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node  "Flush Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Flush Gadget                                                          @{fg text}@{uu}

The  flush  gadget  will flush all entries in the currently  displayed
list from QLibs memory.  It will NOT delete anything from disk.

@endnode


@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node  "Delete Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Delete Gadget                                                         @{fg text}@{uu}

The  delete gadget will delete the currently selected file.  QLib will
confirm this before any action is taken.

@{bg fill}                                                                      @{bg back}
@{fg shine}                           W A R N I N G@{fg text}
If your not too sure about deleting system files or why they are there
then  DO  NOT  delete anything.  The delete button is for the informed
user.   Deleting  a  file  displayed by QLib could disable software on
your system or worse cripple portions of your system.
@{bg fill}                                                                      @{bg back}
@endnode


@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Disable-Enable Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Disable/Enable Gadget                                                 @{fg text}@{uu}

These  two  gadgets allow you to quickly disable/enable any file using
the  disable  string set in your @{"preferences" link "PrefsWindow"}.  QLib will either prefix
or  suffix  the  selected  file name with the disable string.  You can
choose  either  prefix  or suffix by clicking on the appropriate radio
button.

@{bg fill}                                                                      @{bg back}
@{fg shine}                           W A R N I N G@{fg text}
If  your  not  too  sure  about disabling system files or why they are
there  then  DO  NOT  disable anything.  The disable button is for the
informed  user.   Disabling  a  file  displayed  by QLib could disable
software on your system or worse cripple portions of your system.
@{bg fill}                                                                      @{bg back}

@endnode

@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "Iconify Gadget"
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Iconify Gadget                                                        @{fg text}@{uu}

The  main  window  has  an  additional  gadget to the left of the zoom
gadget  in  the  title  bar.  Clicking on this will shut down QLib and
open  a  small  title bar window.  To un-iconify, select the iconified
window and click the right mouse button.
@endnode


@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@node BugsQuirks
@remark--------------------------------------------------------------------
@{fg shine}@{u}
Bugs And Behavior Quirks.                                             @{fg text}@{uu}


  @{fg shine}Bugs:@{fg text}
